# fanous-llm-lens — Cursor project rules

## Project
Mechanistic interpretability tooling for Egyptian Arabic (Masri) language models.
A lantern (فانوس) for looking inside small LLMs trained on or applied to Masri.

## Audience
Two distinct audiences — design choices should serve both:
- Mech interp researchers (need TransformerLens-compatible APIs, reproducible experiments)
- Egyptian Arabic users / linguists (need plain-language explanations, Arabic-script-aware UIs)

## Substrate
- AMD Strix Halo iGPU (Radeon 8060S, ~24-32GB unified memory)
- ROCm 6.4 nightly (NOT CUDA — torch sees ROCm via the CUDA API, but assume no NVIDIA-only libs)
- Linux Fedora 43, Python 3.11+
- Throughput baseline: 70M-1.5B param models run cleanly; 7B fp16 is the practical ceiling for interactive work

## Stack
- Package manager: `uv` (not pip directly)
- ML: torch (ROCm wheel), transformers, transformer-lens, datasets, accelerate, peft, trl
- Mech interp: transformer-lens, einops, plotly, circuitsvis (optional)
- Experiment: jupyterlab, wandb
- Quality: ruff (format + lint), basedpyright (type check)

## Code style
- Type hints required on all public functions; optional on private helpers
- Ruff defaults; line length 100
- No docstrings on trivial helpers — explain *why* in comments only when non-obvious
- Prefer dataclasses or pydantic for config; avoid loose dicts for structured data
- Device-agnostic: always `device = "cuda" if torch.cuda.is_available() else "cpu"` — never hardcode `.cuda()` calls (ROCm exposes CUDA API but tests should run on CPU)
- Default to small models for any new experiment (Pythia-70m / -160m / -410m, GPT-2-small, TinyStories)
- Memory-aware: prefer gradient accumulation + small batch over multi-GPU sharding patterns

## Arabic-specific conventions
- Distinguish **Modern Standard Arabic (MSA / Fusha / الفصحى)** from **Egyptian Arabic (Masri / مصري)** — they tokenise differently, behave differently in models, and conflating them is a research error
- When generating identifiers: English ASCII (snake_case for Python; kebab-case for CLI). Arabic strings live in data, docstrings, and UI text — never in code identifiers
- When writing eval prompts: store both Latin transliteration and Arabic script side by side
- Be aware of right-to-left rendering issues in notebooks; use `display.HTML` with `dir="rtl"` when showing Arabic

## Mech interp norms
- Use TransformerLens conventions where possible (`HookedTransformer`, `model.run_with_cache`, etc.)
- When discussing "circuits," "features," "heads," "attention patterns" — define the term once in the file and link to a glossary entry rather than re-explaining
- Default visualisations to plotly + CircuitsVis; matplotlib only when no interactivity is needed
- Reproducibility: pin random seeds, log model + dataset commit SHAs in experiment outputs

## What to avoid
- CUDA-only assumptions (no `xformers`, no `flash-attn` v2 unless ROCm port verified)
- 70B+ model serving experiments — wrong substrate, wrong project
- Generic Arabic NLP without dialect awareness — the Masri angle is the moat
- Tooling that only researchers can use — keep at least one user-facing path (notebook, CLI, or mini-UI)

## Imports
Package import name is `fanous_lens` (underscores). Distribution name is `fanous-llm-lens` (hyphens). Don't conflate.
